Step1:
\begin{aligned}
&\text{Notice that }(x^2-4)\le0\text{ for }\text{ x in [-2,2]} \text{ and  }{(x^2-4)\ge 0}\text{ for }{x \in[-\infty ,-2]\cup [2,\infty]}\text{ and use properties: }\\
&\text{(1)}{\int_{a}^{b}f = \int_{a}^{c}f~+~\int_{c}^{b}f}
\\
&\text{(2) }{|x| = -x }\text{ for }{x\le0} \text{ and }{|x|=x}\text{ for }{x\ge0}.
\end{aligned}

Explanation1:
\text{$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{-4}^3\left|x^2-4\right| d x &=\int_{-4}^{-2}\left|x^2-4\right| d x+\int_{-2}^{+2}\left|x^2-4\right| d x+\int_2^3\left|x^2-4\right| d x \\
&=\int_{-4}^{-2}\left(x^2-4\right) d x+\int_{-2}^2\left(4-x^2\right) d x+\int_2^3\left(x^2-4\right) d x
\end{aligned}
$}\\
\text{[as $\left|x^2-4\right|=4-x^2$ in $[-2,2]$ and $x^2-4$ in other intervals]}
